				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">How Did Obama Lose American Voters?</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By John Guida			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-11-14T13:10:37+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">November 14, 2014 8:10 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">November 14, 2014 8:10 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/11/opinion/nyto-obama/nyto-obama-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/11/opinion/nyto-obama/nyto-obama-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/11/opinion/nyto-obama/nyto-obama-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000003229552" width="592" height="585" alt=""   /><meta itemprop="height" content="585"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Kevin Lamarque/Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//op-talk.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/11/14/how-did-obama-lose-american-voters/" data-title="How Did Obama Lose American Voters?" data-description="Many observers look to the record â say, the botched rollout of Healthcare.gov â but maybe the president&#039;s disconnect with voters goes to the office, not the man. ">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In December 2012, 56 percent of Americans approved of President Obamaâs leadership. About 40 percent disapproved.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Today, those numbers are <a href="//www.gallup.com/poll/113980/Gallup-Daily-Obama-Job-Approval.aspx">almost precisely reversed</a>, a fact that Democrats were made keenly aware of in the fall campaign and in the midterm elections.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe publicâs confidence is gone, and it doesnât seem to be coming back,â says <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/11/02/opinion/sunday/ross-douthat-how-obama-lost-america.html?_r=0">Ross Douthat at The New York Times</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">So what happened?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Douthat offers not a unified theory but four âpartialâ ones: Republican intransigence, an incomplete economic recovery from the Great Recession, Obamacare and foreign policy crises.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Indeed, partial theories are popular among observers, and many land onÂ similar issues. In anÂ account of Obamaâs second term, Juliet Eilperin and David Nakamura, <a href="//www.washingtonpost.com/politics/where-did-obama-go-wrong/2014/11/03/f0196c0a-61e2-11e4-8b9e-2ccdac31a031_story.html">writing at The Washington Post</a>, detail what amounts to aÂ war of attrition between the White House and Congress, with each side blaming the other for a lack of progress on legislation of any kind.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What all the partiesÂ had to show for it, after multiple failures on policy and a government shutdown, was nothing but disapproval, The Post reporters write: âThe presidentâs approval ratings took a nose dive, and Congressâs were even worse.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">ForÂ <a href="//dish.andrewsullivan.com/2014/11/04/where-did-obama-go-wrong/">Andrew Sullivan at The Dish</a>, âa fanatically obstructionist and increasingly extreme GOPâ wanted to undermine the president with a strategy âhatched privately before Obama even took office.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span style="color: #282828;">âThey judged early on that the real promise of Obama âÂ his ambition to transcend the old politics in favor of pragmatic reform âÂ could be killed if they simply refused to play along,â Mr. Sullivan writes.</span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On the economy, <a href="//www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/us-politics/11150023/Barack-Obama-the-end-of-a-love-affair.html">Peter Foster at The Telegraph</a> says: âSince Mr. Obama took office facing the worst economic crisis since the Great Depression, unemployment has fallen from 10 percent to 6 percent and American businesses have created 10 million new jobs â thatâs more than Japan, Europe and every other advanced economy combined.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Problem is, he adds, many of those âjobs are âMcJobsâ â that is, low-paid and part-time work that donât leave people feeling better off.â On top of that, âin numerical terms, G.D.P. has risen by 8 percent since Mr. Obama took office, but median household incomes are down.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Douthat agrees: âEven with the improving employment picture this recovery is still basically a disappointment, especially for the middle class,â and adds that it âisnât necessarily a case study in the economy not mattering. Itâs an example of voter patience persisting for a while, and finally running out.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe most persuasive answer to the questionâ â where did Obama go wrong? â âwas the botched roll-out of healthcare.gov,â Mr. Sullivan says. âNo one else can be blamed for this, and it hit the presidentâs ratings like a ten-ton truck.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Douthat points to competence as a general concern for the public with this administrationÂ andÂ identifiesÂ the roll-outÂ as a key moment: âThe health care law is Obamaâs signature issue, it remains largely unpopular (even if support for full repeal is weak), and its initial stumbling coincided with the sharpest second-term drop in the presidentâs approval.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Yet for Mr. Sullivan, this is only the start of the narrative: âWhat this superficial version of events misses is what happened next. The truth is: the Obama team subsequently achieved a near-miraculous rescue of Obamacare, achieved real success in enrollment, and have seen core healthcare costs slow down in such a way that could yet shift our long-term fiscal liabilities for the better.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Still, as Mr. Foster points out, âLike George W. Bush after Hurricane Katrina, Mr. Obamaâs approval numbers never recovered from the sight of his flagship piece of legislation capsizing so ignominiously before it had even left the harbour.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Douthat suggests that the president âhad an edge that Democratic politicians often lack: The public trusted him on foreign policy.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But, he writes, one crisis after another â Syria, Ukraine, ISIS, Ebola â eroded that trust and âmade Obamaâs position irrecoverable.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">While acknowledging that Mr. Obamaâs refusal âto engage in the theatrical parts of the presidency looks terrible during crises,â <a href="//www.newrepublic.com/article/120022/obama-better-crisis-manager-media-gives-him-credit">Danny Vinik at The New Republic</a>, like Mr. Sullivan, defends the president on issuesÂ like ISIS, at least on substantive grounds: âItâs more important that the president craft effective policy responses to crises. Obama has done that â and the media coverage has missed it completely, focusing instead on Obamaâs rhetorical shortcomings and downplaying his policy successes.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2014/11/why-president-obama-hasnt-earned-our-approval/382265/">Conor Friedersdorf at The Atlantic</a> has an entirely different log of reasons to disapprove of Mr. Obamaâs performance. His list includes warrantless wiretapping, a failure to punish illegal torture, a costly and ruinous war on drugs, the unacknowledged moral costs of drone strikes, the presidentâs âsecret kill list,â an out-of-control national-security state and the presidentâs persecution of whistle-blowers and journalists whoâve worked with them.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âConfronted with all of those transgressions, more than four in 10 Americans still approve of the job Obama is doing,â Mr. Friedersdorf writes. âAnd most of them are loyal Democrats. Partisanship and tribalism are overriding the moral compass of too many liberals.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">For <a href="//www.salon.com/2014/11/08/where_obama_went_wrong_how_failing_to_seize_the_radical_moment_explains_his_terrible_week/">Elias Isquith at Salon</a>, the root of the presidentâs problems is not to be found in specific events or issues but in his temperament.Â Many moderates see âObamaâs penchant for working from within the system rather than trying to disrupt itâ as a real plus.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But, he asks, was this temperamental conservatism âthe wrong fit for the current era, when major reforms are so desperately neededâ?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Isquith turns back to <a href="//harpers.org/archive/2009/07/barack-hoover-obama/">a 2009 Harperâs article by Kevin Baker</a>, predictingÂ that Mr. Obama would fail, because he would be unable âto seize the radical moment at hand.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">For Mr. Isquith, âRather than recognize how ideological and partisan realignment and polarization had effectively changed the rules of the Senate,â the president went looking for consensus where none existed.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âAt this point, there is no question that President Obama will fall short of initial expectations,â Mr. Isquith says. âBut more than the failure to pass any one particular bill, the disappointment stems from the presidentâs dogged insistence on being a reformer during a radical era.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But perhaps our focus on the presidency is itself skewed. The presidency is the central element in our political system, but as <a href="//www.foreignpolicy.com/articles/2014/10/14/peak_president_american_leadership">Aaron David Miller writes</a>, maybe the problem is our expectation of the presidency itself.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He argues at Foreign Policy (and in his book âThe End of Greatness: Why America Canât Have (and Doesnât Want) Another Great Presidentâ): âThe centrality of the presidency must be reconciled with the limitations of the office and the constraints that bind it. The presidency has always been an implausible, some might even say an impossible, job. But the following mix of challenges and constraints â some old, some new â has made the post-World War II presidency harder still: constitutional and practical constraints on the office itself; the president&#8217;s expanding reach and responsibilities; the expanding role of a government we trust less, even when we demand more from it; America&#8217;s global role; and an intrusive, omnipresent, and nonstop media.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âGreatness in the presidency is too rare to be relevant in our modern times and â driven as it is in our political system by big crisis â too risky and dangerous to be desirable. Our continued search for idealized presidents raises our expectations and theirs, skews presidential performance, and leads to an impossible standard that can only frustrate and disappoint. To sum up: We can no longer have a truly great president, we seldom need one, and, as irrational as it sounds, we may not want one, either.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He concludes: âHistoric greatness in the presidency has gone the way of the dodo. And it is unlikely to return any time soon.â</p>
